PSA: To install #rstats on macOS with homebrew use

`brew install --cask r`

NOT

`brew install r`

The latter does not support pre-built CRAN package binaries!
This means you will have to compile them yourself,  you will run into many more issues and it will take a lot longer.

This could mean that you could run arbitrary functions within the SQLite database without materializing tables into an #RStats data.frame.

But I see definite issues with speed - for scalar functions there would need to be a call back into R for each row. i.e. will be slow.

@mdsumner To actually answer your question: this would make it possible to process large data (stored in a SQLite DB) without having to materialize the actual data into a data.frame in #RStats e.g.

SELECT aggregate_func(x, y, z) FROM terabyte_db GROUP BY every_square_foot_on_earth;

Challenges 
1: How to sanely define arg types + return types for the R function?
2. R functions with single vs multiple args
3: aggregate + window funcs
4. SQLite's concept of type affinity
5. SQLite's concept of innocuous + deterministic UDFs

#RStats

First proof-of-concept - user-defined-functions (UDFs) for SQLite written in #RStats

This is SQLite calling back into R to calculate a (scalar) result.

This is currently a house-of-cards of hacks to get something running at all. https://t.co/WNVjn7pIyp

But for aggregate functions (where an #RStats call is used on a set of results) far fewer calls would be required

There would still be some changeover point where for smaller data, you'd still be better off just materializing the data.frame representation and calculating on that

  cbind(dst = stringdist(.$X1, .$X2)) %>%
  .[order(.$dist),]

Suppose in R, you have the following factor `x` from which you are tring to subset `y` as shown below. Which of the following option would return TRUE? [see_image_1] #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:01042021033052] https://t.co/eAfM3uJ13N
preserved unless `drop=TRUE`, the default value is `drop=FALSE`. As in the above example, since drop isn't specified the factor levels are preserved. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:01042021163031]

Rethinking aggregate func approach due to SQLite's lax type affinity

I won't know R type of a sequence of results until the first non-NULL value from RSQlite

I.e. If RSQlite gives me: NULL, NULL, 12.34 - then type unknown until 3rd value!

#RStats #SQLite #RSQLite

Update: Using #RStats funcs for aggregate calculations on SQLite DBs

Refactored how vectors are accumulated for each group before being passed to aggregate function via "Ragg1()"

Initial timing still favourable compared to #dplyr & #rdatatable https://t.co/vHm9R4E31x

I'm thinking I need to accumulate "sqlite3_value" objects and then make a global decision on the full vector of results.

e.g.
* NULL, NULL, 12.34  - double
* NULL, 12, 1, 3, - integer
* 12, 1, 3, 5.45 - double
* 1, 2, 3, "apple" - character

#RStats #SQLite #RSQLite

There's a distinct impedance mismatch between the flexible type affinity in SQLite and the dynamic types in #RStats

Current challenge: RSQlite stores NA_real as NULL, but in C SQLite will convert NULL back to 0.0 if you naively request it as a  numeric value

This also enables promotion of types if there are multiple different types in a single SQLite value vector (which is possible as SQLite is quite lax about type consistency in a column)

Fair enough that was ambiguous.

[1] "2021-04-04 02:15:00 NZST"

Okay makes sense.

Oh no.

Correct Option: `TRUE NA`. `|` is a vectorized operator which does elementwise operation. It's counterpart `||` is a non-vectorized operator which only compares the first element. Numerical and logical calculations with `NA` #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:05042021163035]

generally returns `NA`. In cases where the result of the operation would be the same for all possible values the `NA` could take, the operation may return this value. In particular, `TRUE | NA` is `TRUE`. Hence in the above #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:05042021163035]

* httr::GET() submissions from Canvas
* waldo::compare() #rstats objs

* praise::praise() if correct
* rmarkdown::render() feedback
* gmailr::gm_send_message() to students

library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)

path<-"data.xlsx"
df1 <- lapply(excel_sheets(path), function(x) read_excel(path, sheet = x))

df2 <- excel_sheets(path)%>% 
  set_names()%>% 
  map(read_excel, path=path)
